alldata <- read.csv('/Users/emmafunderburg/Desktop/Lab/BORICH LAB/2 - CogMap Paper/Demographic Stats/non_nav_data_final - abbreviated_ya.csv')

df_navigation <- read.csv('/Users/emmafunderburg/Desktop/Lab/BORICH LAB/2 - CogMap Paper/Demographic Stats/non_nav_data_final - YA.csv')

alldata$speed <- df_speed$mean

alldata$corsispan <-df_navigation$corsi_span

alldata$trailsmakinga <- df_navigation$trails_a_ct

# add variables sss diff and ssq diff so we can test for normality in these distributions

alldata$sss_diff <- alldata$sss_post - alldata$sss_pre

alldata$ssq_diff <- alldata$ssq_post - alldata$ssq_pre
## running t test on gender

# run Bartlett's test for equal variances

bartlett.test(speed~Gender, data = alldata)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  speed by Gender
## Bartlett's K-squared = 0.0068154, df = 1, p-value = 0.9342
# p-value = 0.9342, fail to reject H0 and can assume equal variance

# run Shapiro-Wilks test for normality

# make data frame for males
df_male <- data.frame(filter(alldata, Gender =="M"))

# make data frame for females
df_female <- data.frame(filter(alldata, Gender =="W"))

# run Shapiro-Wilks test for normality on males
shapiro.test(df_male$speed)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df_male$speed
## W = 0.90237, p-value = 0.266
# p-value = 0.266, can assume normality

shapiro.test(df_female$speed)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df_female$speed
## W = 0.94315, p-value = 0.3574
# p-value = 0.3574, can assume normality

# run two sample t test on gender

alldata %>%
  group_by(Gender) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(speed),
            sd = sd(speed))
## # A tibble: 2 × 3
##   Gender  mean    sd
##   <chr>  <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 M       16.4  3.48
## 2 W       12.1  3.58
t.test(alldata$average_speed ~ alldata$Gender, var.equal = TRUE, data = alldata, alternative = "two.sided")
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  alldata$average_speed by alldata$Gender
## t = 2.9627, df = 24, p-value = 0.00678
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group M and group W is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.313504 7.345956
## sample estimates:
## mean in group M mean in group W 
##        16.39144        12.06171
### p-value = 0.00678 (for two-sided), reject null hypothesis
# alt hypothesis: true diff in means between group M and group W is different than 0
# we reject H0, so our results support the alt hypothesis that diff in means is > 0
## run tests for assumptions

## running t test on handedness

# run Bartlett's test for equal variances

bartlett.test(speed~Handedness, data = alldata)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  speed by Handedness
## Bartlett's K-squared = 0.23365, df = 1, p-value = 0.6288
# p-value = 0.6288, fail to reject H0 and can assume equal variance

# run Shapiro-Wilks test for normality

# make data frame for males
df_right <- data.frame(filter(alldata, Handedness =="R"))

# make data frame for females
df_other <- data.frame(filter(alldata, Handedness =="O"))

# run Shapiro-Wilks test for normality on R handedness
shapiro.test(df_right$speed)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df_right$speed
## W = 0.97259, p-value = 0.7895
# p-value = 0.7895, can assume normality

# run Shapiro-Wilks test for normality on O (L/M) handedness
shapiro.test(df_other$speed)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df_other$speed
## W = 0.93159, p-value = 0.6072
# p-value = 0.6072, can assume normality

# did R vs 'other' or O (combined L and M into one group, labeled as O)

alldata %>%
  group_by(Handedness) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(average_speed),
            sd = sd(average_speed))

## running both Kruskal-Wallis & one way anova for vr experience quantified!

# testing normality assumptions: histogram

hist(alldata$speed)

# testing normality assumptions: Bartlett's test for equal variances

bartlett.test(speed~vr_exp_quantified, data = alldata)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  speed by vr_exp_quantified
## Bartlett's K-squared = 6.0832, df = 2, p-value = 0.04776
# unequal variances! p-value = 0.04776, reject null hypothesis 

# running one way ANOVA on VR experience quantified

anova_vr_quantified <- aov(speed~vr_exp_quantified, data = alldata)
summary(anova_vr_quantified)
##                   Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
## vr_exp_quantified  1   59.4   59.40   4.044 0.0557 .
## Residuals         24  352.5   14.69                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# one-way anova p-value = 0.0557, fail to reject null hypothesis

# running Kruskal-Wallis test on VR experience quantified

kruskal.test(speed~vr_exp_quantified, data = alldata)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  speed by vr_exp_quantified

# p-value = 0.1165, fail to reject null hypothesis
### prepping for correlation tests

# to run a Pearson correlation, you need: 2 continuous variables, expectation of linearity (via scatter plot), no significant outliers, and normal distributions for both continuous variables

# to test for normality, we can use Shapiro-Wilks test

# Shapiro-Wilks test for speed

shapiro.test(alldata$speed)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  alldata$speed
## W = 0.97939, p-value = 0.8608
# p-value = 0.8608, fail to reject H0 & can proceed with assumption of normality
## run correlation test with video game hours per week

# testing for linearity: general idea via scatter plot

ggplot(data = alldata, aes(Video.Game.Experience..hours.per.week., speed)) + geom_point()

# test normality of video game experience

shapiro.test(alldata$Video.Game.Experience..hours.per.week.)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  alldata$Video.Game.Experience..hours.per.week.
## W = 0.75927, p-value = 3.852e-05
# p-value 3.852E-05, reject null hypothesis, cannot assume normality

# run Pearson's (parametric) correlation test

cor.test(alldata$Video.Game.Experience..hours.per.week., alldata$speed, method = "pearson")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  alldata$Video.Game.Experience..hours.per.week. and alldata$speed
## t = 0.91876, df = 24, p-value = 0.3674
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.2186347  0.5335820
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.1843277
# p-value = 0.3674, fail to reject H0, no evidence of significant correlation
# r = 0.1843277

# run Spearman's (non-parametric) correlation test

cor.test(alldata$Video.Game.Experience..hours.per.week., alldata$speed, method = "spearman", exact = FALSE)
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  alldata$Video.Game.Experience..hours.per.week. and alldata$speed
## S = 2261, p-value = 0.2647
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       rho 
## 0.2270171
# cannot compute exact p-value with ties, hence the exact = FALSE argument
# p-value = 0.2647, fail to reject null hypothesis
# rho = 0.2270171
